ingfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beddingfield","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from Bedingfield in Suffolk. The placename is recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Bedingefelda</i>, from the Old English personal name <i>Bēda</i> + the connective particle <i>-ing-</i> ‘associated with, named after’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":30,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":39,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Peter de Bedingfield was born about 1185, in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England as the son of Sir Adam de Bedingfield. He had at least 2 sons. He died about 1226, at the age of 43, and was buried in Bedingfield, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1185–about 1226":"umbes 1185–umbes 1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1215–1245":"1215–1245","–Male":"Surnud","1151–1205":"1151–1205","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1226":"umbes 1226","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","about 1185":"umbes 1185","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1185–about 1226":"noin 1185–noin 1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1215–1245":"1215–1245","–Male":"Kuollut","1151–1205":"1151–1205","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1226":"noin 1226","about 1205":"noin 1205","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","about 1185":"noin 1185","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1185–about 1226":"environ 1185–environ 1226","1185–1226":"1185–1226","1215–1245":"1215–1245","–Male":"Décédé","1151–1205":"1151–1205","1205":"1205","1226":"1226","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","about 1226":"environ 1226","about 1205":"environ 1205","1185":"1185","1151":"1151","about 1185":"environ 1185","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bedingfield, Suffolk, England":"Bedingfield, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Peter de Bedingfield est né environ 1185, à Bedingfiel